t night. Russell Leigh Sharman and Cheryl Harris Sharman spent a year interviewing and shadowing fry cooks and coffee jockeys, train conductors, cab hacks, and dozens of others who keep the city running when the sun goes down. Investigating familiar places such diners and delis, they explore some less familiar ones as well—taking us on a walking tour of homelessness in Manhattan, onto a fishing boat out of Brooklyn, and into other little-known corners of the night. Traveling past the threshold of voyeurism into the lives of real people, they depict a social space entirely apart—one that is highly structured and inherently subversive. Together, these stories open a compelling view on contemporary urban life and, along the way, reveal the soul of the city itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNight peoplezNew York (State)zNew York. 0aNight workzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafter dark.  aanthropology.  abrooklyn.  acab drivers.  acity dwellers.  acity life.  acity workers.  acoffee.  acontemporary new york.  acrowded cities.  acultural critique.  aculture.  adelis.  adiners.  afishing boats.  afry cooks.  agraveyard shift.  ahomelessness.  ainterviews.  alife and culture.  amanhattan.  amen and women.  anew york city.  anight life.  anight owls.  anight workers.  anightshift.  anonfiction.  aphotographs.  asocial relationships.  atrain conductors.  aunited states.  aurban life.  aworking at night.1 aSharman, Cheryl Harris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025271440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094206640uhttps://www.de